They broke up about 3 years before Christian met Ana because Leila, like Ana, wanted more and Christian didn't. So they break up and Leila gets married and everything is normal. But after she leaves her husband and he washes his hands of her, she finds a new boyfriend, Geoff, who dies in a car accident. So, she then goes insane and heads over to Christians apartment and slashes her wrist in a suicide attempt and a cry for help in front of his housekeeper Gail. Christian is informed of the situation while out gliding with Ana and immediately goes back to Seattle to visit Leila in the hospital. He lies and says he's Leila's brother in order to get access to her to but by the time he reaches her, she's discharged herself and goes missing. She then sees Ana leaving work and runs into her, asking her what she has that she doesn't and when Ana ask's who she is, she replies "I'm Nobody". She leaves and later gets a gun licence and trespasses in the apartment several times, watching Ana and Christian sleeping and going through some of their things. Ana sees Leila at one point (as you see in the trailer at 1:28) but then thinks that it's just a dream, but after they notice windows have been left open, they realise that it was Leila and she's still in the apartment. Leila gets better and Ana meets up with her in Freed and Leila and her friend Suzi(who also was one of Christians ex-submissive's, they call themselves the sub-club), and she reveals why she went so crazy and how she loved Geoff and Christian etc; and they both go off and live their lives happily ever after! text: I love these movies, and fuck all you "normies" out there who don't. This movie speaks for all the freaks, geeks, and weirdo's who just have an inward frustration that they can't come to terms with. It's normalizing things that people struggle with and are forced to hide every single day of their lives. Just think for one minute how awful it must be to hide something that makes you feel so good. It's like living a lie. It's like punching yourself in the face every time you get a boner. It's like watching everyone around you eat food and you're forced to eat paper. There's nothing wrong with having fetishes and philia's. It's a natural thing that just comes to be. Don't kick people while they are down who are going thru life with these problems. Everyone has their own issues. Some people are addicted to drugs, some are addicted to certain sexual tendencies. Let them be. I applaud this movie for pushing the envelope and bringing to light a dark world that is always overlooked or swept under the rug.
